Some flaws there are in the story. Although Julia is at the end a spotless bride, her conduct has not been above reproach. And her father, whose surgical operation has been postponed‚ is left at the end of the play with this unpleasant prospect still before him. While Pantomagus has renounced his suit after discovering Julia’s rather free behaviour, we hear nothing of the manner in which F redericus bears bis defeat.

A little concession is made to a Cambridge audience when the scene is transferred from Salerno to Padua‚ the seat of a famous university‚ and when the hero is made a student sent to Padua from Venice. Opportunity is thus given for some
